{
  "description": {
    "title": "Non-carbon showcase: an RPS/REC obligation market — buyout (ACP) bit-for-bit, investment-triggered renewable entry, zero new mechanism code",
    "paper": "docs/platform-spec-d0-d1.md §1/§8 (ets-lead-economist design gate, 2026-07-11). Reinterpretation: penalty_price is an obligation-EXTINGUISHING buyout (§1.1) -- exactly the RPS Alternative Compliance Payment; a technology_option's investment_trigger block (docs/invest-feedback-spec.md) reused verbatim for renewable capacity entry. Proves the engine generalizes beyond carbon with the SAME kernel code -- only flow_label/flow_unit/price_unit (display-only, D0-R2) differ from a carbon example.",
    "mechanism": "One obligated aggregate retailer must cover a rising RPS-implied obligation (initial_emissions, reinterpreted per §1 as RPS% × 500 TWh) every year, entirely off-market (auction_offered 0 -- OTC clearing at net demand 0, no centrally auctioned volume). The retailer itself carries zero abatement capacity (abatement_type threshold, max_abatement 0) so it always relies on genuine counterparties: two always-available self-supply participants (B1 60 TWh @ $8/MWh, B2 50 TWh @ $22/MWh, modelled as 100%-free-allocated threshold sellers -- the idiomatic way this engine represents a tiered MAC supply curve feeding a market) plus a THIRD, initially-unavailable offshore-wind tranche (B3, 40 TWh @ $38/MWh) carried as a flagged technology_option on its own placeholder participant (inert until adopted -- base fields all zero, spec D2.5 'flagged option DELETED until adopted'). B3's investment_trigger (break_even_price theta=40, trigger_mode break_even so M≡1, payout_yield required-but-inert under break_even, build_lag_years 0) reuses the endogenous-investment feature unmodified: the outer loop reads the DELIVERED price of the masked (pre-adoption) path, dates the first year it crosses theta, and re-solves with B3 unmasked from that year on.",
    "inputs": "years 2026-2030; obligation (RPS% × 500 TWh) 50/70/90/120/150 TWh; buyout (ACP) = penalty_price 45 USD/MWh on the retailer; flow_label REC, flow_unit TWh, price_unit USD/MWh (revenue columns read as $M since $1/MWh ≡ $1M/TWh, spec §8); competitive, static (no banking) -- model_approach competitive, banking_allowed false every year.",
    "expected_output": {
      "pre-adoption (B3-deleted, V3-equivalent) prices 2026-2030": [8.0, 22.0, 22.0, 45.0, 45.0],
      "pre-adoption note": "buyout binds 2029: obligation 120 TWh crosses the below-ACP self-supply capacity (B1+B2 = 110 TWh); the ACP (45) mechanically caps the price -- Brent's-method convergence lands a few 1e-12 below 45.0 (well inside atol 1e-6), and the retailer's own penalty_emissions bookkeeping stays 0 (all 10 TWh of shortfall reports as 'Allowance Buys' at the uniform clearing price rather than 'Penalty Emissions') because the clearing price never numerically exceeds the retailer's own penalty_price threshold -- a known solver-boundary artifact of a monopsonist-only demand side, NOT a config error. The genuine settlement volume (10 TWh in 2029, 40 TWh in 2030) is robustly recoverable as obligation minus delivered self-supply (Total Abatement) and is dollar-equivalent to a buyout since price == ACP.",
      "adoption year": "2029 -- the first year the masked (pre-adoption) delivered price (45) crosses theta=40 (break_even mode, M≡1, P*=40); build_lag_years 0 so B3 is available the SAME year.",
      "final (post-adoption) prices 2026-2030": [8.0, 22.0, 22.0, 38.0, 40.131579],
      "final note": "2029 = 38.0 exactly (B1+B2+B3 = 150 TWh capacity vs 120 TWh obligation -- a clean crossing); 38 < theta(40) exercises the D1.1 ex-post-regret INFO log (adopted pair below its trigger on the final path -- permitted, discrete-entry regret). 2030 is a KNOWN DISCREPANCY from the hand-calculated 38: obligation (150) EXACTLY equals total capacity (60+50+40=150) that year, so net demand is identically zero across the ENTIRE [38, 45] price band (no shortfall, but no excess supply either until the retailer's own 45 threshold also drops out) -- an economically indeterminate tie that Brent's method resolves to an arbitrary point inside that band (empirically ~40.13, deterministic given fixed scipy/numpy versions) rather than the conventional 'marginal cost of the last unit used' (38). The PHYSICAL outcome is unaffected (zero shortfall, obligation fully self-supplied at 150 TWh) -- only the displayed marginal price differs. Flagged for economist review per docs/platform-plan-d0-d1.md D0-R4 (report discrepancies, never silently retune the calibration)."
    },
    "run": "PYTHONPATH=src .venv/bin/python -m pe.cli --config examples/showcase_rps_rec.json"
  },
